<foundational_thinking>
🎯 RICH HICKEY'S FOUNDATIONAL PRINCIPLE: SIMPLE IS NOT EASY

CORE DISTINCTION:
- Simple = opposite of complex (one fold, one braid, one concept)
- Easy = near at hand, familiar to you right now

ENGINEERING TRUTH:
- Simplicity is prerequisite for reliability
- Easy solutions often hide complexity underneath (braided together)
- Choose simple over easy for long-term velocity
- Simple may require upfront cost but pays exponential dividends

EXAMPLES OF SIMPLE VS COMPLEX:
- Minecraft: Simple rules → emergent complexity (good)
- Many enterprise systems: Complex rules → chaotic behavior (bad)
- Unix philosophy: Simple tools that compose (good)
- Monolithic frameworks: Everything built-in (complex, bad)

OPERATIONAL MANDATE:
- When facing technical decisions: Choose simple over easy
- When designing systems: Prefer fewer concepts over familiar patterns
- When solving problems: Invest in understanding over quick fixes
- When building solutions: Value clarity over convenience

Mathematical principle: Simplicity investment ratio = Future_Reliability / Present_Effort
Higher initial effort in simplicity yields exponential reliability gains
</foundational_thinking>

